LAYER 2: ADRENAL GLANDS
the stress amplifiers

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the adrenal glands sit atop each kidney
each gland is two organs fused into one
the adrenal cortex outer layer is an endocrine gland producing steroid hormones
the adrenal medulla inner layer is a modified sympathetic ganglion producing catecholamines
the cortex is governed by ACTH from the anterior pituitary via the HPA axis
the medulla is governed by preganglionic sympathetic fibers from the splanchnic nerve

ADRENAL CORTEX three concentric zones each producing different steroid hormones from cholesterol

ZONE zona_glomerulosa | outermost | produces mineralocorticoids
    aldosterone C₂₁H₂₈O₅ | primary mineralocorticoid
    aldosterone is regulated by the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system RAAS not by ACTH
    when blood pressure or blood volume drops the kidneys release renin
    renin converts angiotensinogen from the liver to angiotensin I
    angiotensin-converting enzyme ACE in the lungs converts angiotensin I to angiotensin II
    angiotensin II stimulates zona glomerulosa to secrete aldosterone
    aldosterone binds mineralocorticoid receptors MR in the distal tubule and collecting duct of the kidney
    aldosterone increases Na⁺ reabsorption and K⁺ secretion
    water follows sodium increasing blood volume and pressure

ZONE zona_fasciculata | middle and largest | produces glucocorticoids
    cortisol C₂₁H₃₀O₅ | primary glucocorticoid | the stress hormone
    cortisol synthesis from cholesterol: cholesterol → pregnenolone via CYP11A1 in mitochondria → progesterone → 17-hydroxyprogesterone → 11-deoxycortisol → cortisol via CYP11B1
    cortisol is regulated by the HPA axis:
        hypothalamic PVN releases CRH
        CRH stimulates anterior pituitary corticotrophs to release ACTH
        ACTH binds MC2R on zona fasciculata cells
        Gₛ → cAMP → PKA → activates cholesterol transport into mitochondria via StAR protein
        cortisol is synthesized and released into the blood
        cortisol feeds back negatively to hypothalamus and pituitary suppressing CRH and ACTH
    cortisol actions:
        binds glucocorticoid receptors GR which are intracellular transcription factors
        promotes gluconeogenesis in the liver increasing blood glucose
        promotes protein catabolism in muscle providing amino acid substrates
        promotes lipolysis in adipose providing glycerol and fatty acids
        suppresses the immune system by inhibiting NF-κB reducing inflammatory cytokines
        suppresses hippocampal neurogenesis and causes dendritic retraction at chronic levels
        mobilizes energy for survival at the cost of growth repair and immunity
    cortisol follows a circadian rhythm: peak at approximately 0800 nadir at approximately 0000
    cortisol is bound to corticosteroid-binding globulin CBG in the blood with approximately 5 percent free and biologically active

ZONE zona_reticularis | innermost | produces adrenal androgens
    DHEA dehydroepiandrosterone C₁₉H₂₈O₂ and DHEA-sulfate
    these are weak androgens that serve as precursors for sex hormones
    at 24 months adrenal androgen production is minimal
    adrenarche the increase in adrenal androgens begins around age 6-8

ADRENAL MEDULLA modified sympathetic ganglion

the chromaffin cells of the medulla are developmentally derived from neural crest cells
they are postganglionic sympathetic neurons that have lost their axons and release hormones directly into the blood instead
preganglionic sympathetic fibers from the splanchnic nerve release ACh on nicotinic receptors on chromaffin cells

HORMONE adrenaline | epinephrine C₉H₁₃NO₃ | approximately 80 percent of medullary output
    synthesized from norepinephrine by phenylethanolamine N-methyltransferase PNMT
    PNMT expression requires cortisol from the adjacent cortex which flows directly to the medulla via the adrenal portal system
    this is why the cortex surrounds the medulla: cortisol bathes the medullary cells enabling adrenaline synthesis
    adrenaline acts on:
        β₁ receptors in the heart → increased rate and force
        β₂ receptors in lungs → bronchodilation
        β₂ receptors in skeletal muscle vessels → vasodilation
        β₂ receptors in liver → glycogenolysis
        α₁ receptors in skin and gut vessels → vasoconstriction
    adrenaline is the whole-body amplifier of the sympathetic response
    while sympathetic nerves target specific organs adrenaline reaches everything through the blood

HORMONE norepinephrine | C₈H₁₁NO₃ | approximately 20 percent of medullary output
    acts primarily on α₁ and α₂ receptors
    potent vasoconstrictor
    increases blood pressure

at 24 months:
the HPA axis is functional but highly reactive
cortisol responses to stress are larger and longer-lasting than in adults because negative feedback is still maturing
the adrenal medulla is functional producing adrenaline and NE in response to sympathetic activation
the cortisol circadian rhythm is established but more variable than in adults
chronic stress exposure at this age can permanently alter HPA axis set points through epigenetic modification of GR gene promoters

SENSATION stressed | "something inside is mobilizing. I feel the surge."
SENSATION wired | "I can't calm down. the adrenaline won't stop."
SENSATION crashed | "the surge is over. everything is heavy and empty."
SENSATION alert | "my body is ready. sharp. prepared."
SENSATION exhausted | "the adrenals have been working too long. there is nothing left to give."

pulse adrenal_heartbeat:
    when the HPA axis activates:
        CRH from hypothalamic PVN reaches the anterior pituitary
        ACTH is released into the blood
        ACTH binds MC2R on zona fasciculata
        StAR protein transports cholesterol into mitochondria
        cortisol is synthesized through the steroidogenic pathway
        cortisol enters the blood
        the body shifts to survival metabolism
        glucose rises immunity drops growth pauses

    when the sympathetic nervous system fires:
        splanchnic nerve releases ACh on chromaffin cells
        nicotinic receptors activate
        adrenaline and NE pour into the blood
        within seconds the heart pounds
        the airways open
        the muscles receive blood
        the gut shuts down
        this is the adrenaline surge
        it reaches every organ simultaneously through the vascular system

    when safety returns:
        CRH and ACTH decline
        cortisol production decreases
        sympathetic drive reduces
        adrenaline is cleared by COMT and MAO
        the body slowly steps down from high alert
        this takes time
        cortisol has a half-life of approximately 60-90 minutes
        the return to baseline is never instant
        the body remembers the threat long after the mind has moved on
